  <h1>20 Tips to Create Better Prompts</h1>
  <p class="subtitle">Your quick cheat sheet for working smarter with ChatGPT</p>
  <ol>
    <li>Be specific about what you want – e.g., "Write a friendly reminder email about an upcoming dentist appointment" is better than "Write an email."</li>
    <li>State the format you expect – like “Make a list,” “Write a dialogue,” “Use bullet points.”</li>
    <li>Mention the audience – e.g., "Explain black holes to a 10-year-old" vs. "Explain black holes to a physics student."</li>
    <li>Add background info – e.g., “I run a local bakery and need ideas for Instagram posts.”</li>
    <li>Describe the goal – “Help me come up with a persuasive argument for this blog post.”</li>
    <li>Include tone or style – “Write it in a casual, friendly tone” or “Make it sound professional.”</li>
    <li>Assign a role – e.g., “Act like a travel agent planning a budget trip to Italy.”</li>
    <li>Use scenarios – “Pretend you're helping someone plan their wedding speech.”</li>
    <li>Start small, then build – First ask “Give me ideas for a presentation,” then follow up with “Turn idea #2 into an outline.”</li>
    <li>Use step-by-step instructions – Ask: “Walk me through the process of…”</li>
    <li>Ask for revisions – “Make it shorter,” “Use simpler language,” or “Add a joke.”</li>
    <li>Chain prompts together – Use follow-ups: “Great. Now turn that into a catchy title.”</li>
    <li>Try: “Give me 10 ideas for…” – Great for brainstorming.</li>
    <li>Try: “Summarize this text in 3 bullet points.”</li>
    <li>Try: “Compare X and Y in a table.”</li>
    <li>Mix styles or voices – “Explain AI like a pirate” or “Write this like a fairy tale.”</li>
    <li>Use fun challenges – “Create a fake news headline about cats running the government.”</li>
    <li>Avoid vague words like “good” or “better” – Be precise: “More exciting,” “Shorter,” “For teens.”</li>
    <li>Avoid too many questions in one prompt – Split them up to get clearer answers.</li>
    <li>Ask ChatGPT how to improve your prompt – literally say: “How can I ask this better?” or “What info would you need to give a better answer?”</li>
  </ol>
</body>
